<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-577-491  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 577 491.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Nov 1990 v15 n12 p466(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Stomping the nasties. (a guide top computer viruses )</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kenner, Hugh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses differ from other forms of computer invaders,like worms, logic bombs, and Trojan horses, in that they have theability to replicate.andP;  After entering a system embedded in a hostprogram, the virus separates and searches for other hosts toattach itself to.andP;  A common strain of virus attacks the bootsector of an operating system, replacing it with a corruptedsector that can control the system the next time the computer isswitched on.andP;  Three types of antivirus products are on the market.andO;The first attempts to repel a virus, but can be confused by normalprogram functions, and is susceptible to boot viruses which takeeffect before the antivirus program is loaded.andP;  The secondattempts to disarm the virus as it arrives by noting any minutechanges in the operating system.andP;  The third cleans up virusesafter they have taken effect, but these need constant updating asnew strains are discovered.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesGuidelinesAccess Controls.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>